social_posts.post_text: It’s the 12 Days of Kindness. Today’s tip? Smile at a stranger or say hi. It could make their day. It will definitely make yours!

I know this will be a big one for some of us, but I’m convinced that it’s our only way back to kindness and compassion. 

Grab a coffee with someone who’s views you don’t share and try to find some common ground together.

Third day of kindness…

Be kind on social media. Negative words and messages are painful (trust me…). None of us know what the person on the receiving end of that ugly comment is going through; comment as you would like to be spoken to: with kindness and compassion, even if you disagree. Ok?

Day 4 of Kindness

Maybe skip texting or commenting in all caps. That’s yelling and no one likes that. Breathe and think before you post, ok?

Today’s Kindness…

Leave your phone in your bag or pocket if you’re in a shop, coffeehouse, restaurant, bank…etc. The people you interact with there for service aren’t invisible and deserve our respect and gratitude. Acknowledging them will make their day and yours.

12 Days of Kindness Day 6:
Pass your parking spot to the car behind you that’s also looking for a place. You’ll lose nothing and gain everything.

12 Days of Kindness Day 7: 
Allow someone to go ahead of you in line at the market. You might lose a little time, but you’ll gain a smile from a stranger.

12 Days of Kindness Day 8: 
Babysit for a new mom so she can have some time to take care of herself.

12 Days of Kindness
Bake some cookies and deliver them to your local firehouse or police station. You’ll light up their day as you thank them for their service.

12 Days of Kindness Day 10:
Make a pot of soup and share it with some neighbors. It would be great to eat together, but if time won’t allow for that, just drop off a lovely container of homemade soup. It will warm their tummies and their hearts.

This is my puréed Pasta e Fagioli with the pasta on top. Recipe will be on my site soon.

12 Days of Kindness Day 11:
Check in on a neighbor and be sure they are ok. Young or old, we all need someone to care.

12 Days of Kindness Day 12:
Take a breath before losing your temper…and be kind each and every day.

🎙️ On the Chefs Without Restaurants podcast this week (link in bio) I have chef Christina Pirello of @ChristinaCooks. After already losing her mother to cancer, Christina was diagnosed with terminal leukemia in her mid-20s. Not wanting to undergo traditional treatment for cancer, she ultimately switched to a vegan diet and her cancer went into remission. She’s been cancer-free for more than 37 years now.⁣
⁣
🥕 Christina wanted to share what she’d learned about food and cooking, and Christina Cooks was born. She started a cooking show on PBS (and won an Emmy in her first season) and has published numerous cookbooks. While Christina maintains a vegan diet, she isn’t preachy about it.⁣ We talked about her early days working in a professional kitchen, her journey to wellness, and how she built and grew the Christina Cooks brand.⁣

Messing with a new apple-crumb cake recipe today. Here’s what I did. 

Preheat oven to 350 and oil a 6-inch cake pan. 

Finely dice 1/2 apple and set aside.

Mix together 2T olive oil, 4 T coconut sugar, 4T chopped nuts, 4T @lindleymills sprouted whole wheat flour to form crumbs.

In a mixing bowl, whisk together 1 1/2 c sprouted flour, 1/2 c coconut sugar, pinch salt and cinnamon. Mix in 1/4 cup olive oil, 1 recipe @bobsredmill egg replacer in 1/4 water, 1 tsp vanilla and 1 cup water. Stir to form a thick batter. Fold in apples and spoon into oiled pan. Spread it evenly and top with crumbles. 

Bake for 35-40 minutes or til the top springs back to the touch. 

I served it on my fave @ceramichedarte_carmela plate.

Enjoy!!!

Can there be a St Patrick’s Day celebration without Irish Soda Bread? I think not. Here’s how I made mine. 

Stir 1 T Apple cider vinegar and 2 T olive oil into 200ml of oat milk. Let it curdle for 5 min. 

Mix together 2 3/4 c sprouted whole wheat flour, 1 tsp sea salt and 1 T baking soda.

Mix all together to form a soft dough. Fold in 1/2 cup chopped walnuts. 

Form into a round ball and place on a lightly floured baking sheet. Cut a cross deeply into the dough. Bake at 350F for 30 min. It should feel hollow when you tap the bottom. 

Cook’s Tip: you can add a bit of coconut sugar and raisins or currants to make a sweet soda bread. Or add caraway seeds to this recipe. I chose walnuts because…well…we like them.

Ever have a day when the only thing that’s going to satisfy you is a really really good brownie??? That was today for me so I took a deep breath and took a stab at it. Vegan brownies are often too cake-like. These babies are simply perfect…I’m soooooooooo happy. It’s the little things. 

Vegan Brownies
These babies are so fudgy and yummy, I am over the moon.

Makes 12-16 brownies

½ cup extra virgin olive oil, warmed
1 cup coconut sugar
⅓ cup non-dairy milk (I used oat)
3 teaspoons pure vanilla extract
1 cup sprouted whole wheat flour
¾ cup unsweetened cocoa powder
¾ teaspoon baking powder
¼ teaspoon salt
1 cup dark, non-dairy chocolate chips

Preheat the oven to 350°F (325 if using convection). Lightly oil an 8
x 8-inch baking pan and line it with parchment on the bottom (and oil
that paper).

Whisk together the warmed oil, coconut sugar, milk and vanilla until
smooth. Slowly mix in flour, cocoa powder, baking powder and salt.
Fold in chocolate chips and mix so they are well-incorporated.

Spoon into the prepared pan and smooth evenly with a spatula. Bake for
25-30 minutes. The sides of the brownies should pull away from the
pan and the center should be quite soft, but not raw-looking.

Allow to stand for 10-15 minutes before cutting into squares.

Almond Chocolate Chip Cardamom Cookies

6 tablespoons coconut sugar
5 tablespoons avocado or olive oil
1 teaspoon chia seeds dissolved in 3 tablespoons water
1 teaspoon pure vanilla extract
generous pinch sea salt
1 1/2 cups blanched almond flour
1/2 cup rolled oats
1/2 teaspoon baking soda
3/4 teaspoon cardamom
4 ounces non-dairy, dark chocolate chips
1/2 cup shelled pistachios

Preheat oven to 350o F (325 F convection) and line a baking sheet with
parchment.

Whisk together coconut sugar, oil, chia, vanilla and salt until
smooth. mix in almond flour, oats, baking soda, chocolate and
pistachios to form a stiff cookie dough.

Using a tablespoon measure, spoon dough onto lined baking sheet. You
will have 24-27 cookies.

Bake for 12 minutes or until the edges are golden.

Cool completely before putting in a sealed container.

Cook's tip: Using a spatula, I lightly pressed my cookies a bit
flatter when they came out of the oven.

1/2 c farro, rinsed
2 c water
Extra virgin olive oil
2 cloves garlic, coarse chop
Sea salt

First videos with my new ‘glasses’ I promise I’ll get better at this!!! But here’s a simple blueberry coffee cake series and here’s the recipe:

Blueberry Coffee Cake
Topping
4 T coconut sugar
4 T olive oil
Splash vanilla 
Pinch sea salt
1/3 c @lindleymills sprouted flour

Cake
5T coconut sugar
1/4 c olive oil 
1 tsp vanilla
Grated zest of 1/2 lemon
1 egg replacer, dissolved 
1 tsp baking powder
Pinch sea salt 
1 1/4 c sprouted flour
3/4-1 c water
1/2 c blueberries 

Make the topping by mixing the ingredients together to create a soft crumbly dough. Set aside. 

Make the cake. Mix the wet ingredients together and then mix in the dry. Stir in water til a smooth batter forms. Fold in blueberries. Spoon into an oiled and floured 6-inch pan. Crumble streusel on top. 

Bake in a preheated 350o F oven (325 for convection) for 35 min or til the top bounces back to the touch. 

Enjoy!!!

It’s stay home and cook Saturday ( just like almost every other Saturday in our house). Baking for cookie orders so I made a simple lunch of Kasha with Noodles, Seitan and Veg. Here’s what I did:

1/2 c kasha (toasted)
1/2 c small pasta like bow ties
1 1/4 c water
Pinch salt
1/4 each small dice onion, celery, carrot
Extra virgin olive oil
1 scallion, thinly sliced 
1 clove finely diced garlic
Small knob ginger, diced
1 small hot pepper, diced
1/2 carrot, fine matchstick pieces
1 cup seitan, diced
3-4 leaves Chinese cabbage
Shredded
Mushrooms if your choice, 
sliced 
Small Romesco florets
Soy sauce

Dry pan toast kasha til fragrant (even though it’s toasted) 

Bring water to the boil with a pinch of salt. Add diced vegetables. Add toasted kasha and pasta, stir and cook for 10 minutes over low heat. 

Sauté scallion, garlic, ginger and chili in a small amount of oil with a pinch of salt. Add balance of veggies 1 at a time with a pinch of salt each time. Spoon kasha on top; add a tiny amount of water; reduce heat to low and cook, covered for 7 minutes. 

Stir well and enjoy!!!

Came up with these cookies today. Tis the season. Right? Here’s what I did:
Chocolate Chip Almond Cookies

8 tablespoons olive oil
1/4 c brown rice syrup 
6 T coconut sugar
1 tsp pure vanilla extract
2 T arrowroot powder
2T water
Pinch sea salt
1 tsp cinnamon (seems like a lot but trust me)
1 c sprouted whole wheat flour
1/2 c almond flour
1/2 tsp baking soda
1/2 tsp baking powder
1/2 c slivered almonds
1 3.5 oz dark chocolate bar, coarsely chopped

Preheat oven to 350o F and line 2 baking sheets with parchment. 

Whisk together oil, sweeteners, vanilla, arrowroot, water, salt and cinnamon until smooth and creamy. Mix in flours and baking soda and powder to create a smooth cookie batter. Fold in nuts and chocolate until well-incorporated. 

Spoon by tablespoons onto lined trays leaving space for them to grow. Bake for 13 minutes. Allow to cool until the chopped chocolate sets up. 

They’re sooooo good. Make these!!!

Made a yummy pot pie for lunch today. Here’s what I did.
 
I sautéed 1/2 yellow onion in olive oil with a pinch of salt. Added 1/2 diced zucchini, 1 small potato, diced, 1 small diced carrot, 5 shredded Brussels sprouts, 1/2 c frozen peas and 1/2 cup shredded seitan. Seasoned lightly with sea salt, added a small amount of water and simmered for 10 min while I made the crust. 

For the crust, I mixed 1 cup sprouted whole wheat flour with 1/4 c olive oil, a pinch of salt and just enough water to pull the dough into a ball. Rolled it out between parchment. 

Preheat through oven to 350o F and lightly oil the rim of a pie plate with olive oil. 

Using a small amount of arrowroot with cold water, stir into the veggies to make a clear sauce. Spoon evenly into pie plate. Top with crust and crimp the edges. Brush lightly with olive oil and bake for 30 min.

I have mastered Vegan Canele’. I’ll say upfront that if you don’t have a baking scale, get one for this yummy recipe alone. I’m also not a super-precise baker but I am for this recipe to work. But they’re soooooooo delicious that it’s worth this bit of precision. 

Here is what I did: 

205 g oat milk
100 g coconut sugar
15 g vegan butter
2 tsp vanilla extract
1/2 tsp orange extract
65 g sprouted whole wheat flour
1 T bobs red mill egg replacer
1/2 tsp baking powder
Pinch sea salt

Mix together oat milk, coconut sugar and vegan butter in a small sauce pan over medium low heat and cook stirring occasionally until the butter melts. Stir in vanilla and orange extracts.

In the meantime, sift together flour, egg replacer, baking powder and salt. 

Pour the oat milk mixture over the flour mixture slowly while whisking to create a smooth, quite loose batter. 

Cover the batter with plastic and refrigerate for 24 hours or more. 

Bring batter to room temperature. Preheat oven to 475o F. Melt a tablespoon of vegan butter and pour it into 4 copper molds. Brush and roll the oil around to coat the insides of the little molds. 

Pour batter into the molds to fill 3/4 full. Bake for 10 minutes at 475oF. Reduce heat to 350oF. Bake for 55 minutes more. 

Take the molds out of the oven and immediately turn them out onto a cooling rack. 

As they cool, the exterior will take on a crisp texture and the interior will have a custard cake-like texture. 

Try them, but get the right molds. Copper molds are the best. Hard molds are best but skip silicone if you can. 

Makes 4 canele’.
